The dataset I am analysing is constructed based on a survey conducted in an introductory statistics course in University of Helsinki. It consists of the exam points and three different variables measuring respondents qualities as a student, along with data for some background characteristics. Overall, there are 166 observations (i.e., students) and 7 variables in the dataset.

Typical student in the dataset is a young female. Indeed, the median respondents age is 22 years old, while circa 66% of the students identify themselves as females. As for the exam points and the variables measuring students learning qualities, they appear approximately normally distributed.

Considering connections between variables, it is hard distinguish clear cut linear relationships. Based on visual examination and simple correlation coefficients, too patterns could be pointed out, however. At first look, students attitude and exam points appear to be positively correlated, while their deep learning qualities and surface learning features are negatively correlated. This was expected.

I chose students attitude, age and deep learning skills as predictors of exam points. Turns out, that only attitude can explain exam points with a relatively good precision: it is statistically significant at the 0.001% level in the model including all three variables. Attitude and age lack statistical significance at the 10% level, and thus I exclude them from the second model. In the second, bivariate model attitude is again significant at the 0.001% level, and its coefficient remains virtually unchanged. The coefficients interpretation is, that conditional on age and deep learning skills, a one-point increase in attitude (ranging from 14 to 50) predicts an increase of ~0.36 points in exam.

Looking at the value on multiple R-squared in the first linear model (m1), I can conclude that the three explanatory variables can explain around 20% of the variation in exam points.

Q5. Diagnostic plots

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(m2, which = c(1, 2, 5))

The linear model I estimated assumes, that its error terms follow a normal distribution, i.e.they have a mean zero, a constant variance and experience no autocorrelation. Based on the distribution of error term estimates, the residuals, this assumption appears to be roughly accurate. The residuals are centered around zero, and they do not share a tendency to variate with respect to the fitted values. In addition, none of the observations seem to possess exceptionally high leverage in terms of regression coefficients: none scores particularly high value on Cooks distance relative to others.

The dataset I am working with consist of 35 different features regarding demographics, studies and social life of 382 Portuguese students. Speficially, it includes data on grades and alcohol consumption.

Q3. Picking explanatory variables

My analysis pursues to study whether a relatively high level of alcohol consumption among students could be predicted based on social treats. To do this, I have picked four variables for closer examination. The variables are the following:

Medu - mothers education, ranging from none to higher education

studytime - weekly study time, ranging from less than 2 hours to over 10 hours

activities - extra-curricular activities, with binary response.

Pstatus - parents cohabitation status, with binary response

In short, I hypothesise that mothers education, study time and extra-curricular activities are negatively associated with high levels of alcohol consumption. For parents cohabitation status, I predict that with no cohabitation the risk of high alcohol consumption is greater.

Based on quick numerical and graphical exploration, I could make the following observations. Considering my explanatory variables, the distribution of mothers educations appears to be rightly skewed, while study time is skewed to the left. In words, this implies that in the sample at hand, the students mothers tend to have at least some education, and typically higher education. Moreover, a weekly study time of 2 to 5 hours is the most common, while higher numbers are seemingly less prevalent. In addition, participation to extracurricular activities splits the sample virtually in half. Finally, the great majority of students parents live in cohabitation.

Moving on to connections between variables, the accuracy of my hypotheses is at best mixed. The most precise prediction is the one on study time, which is negatively correlated with high levels of alcohol consumption. All the other correlations are very close to zero, and the sign on mothers education is actually positive.

Next, I ran a logistic regression using the aforementioned four variables as explanatory variables. Not surprisingly, the model by and large confirms what the correlation coefficients suggested: apart from study time, the selected variables cannot help us identify students with high levels of alcohol consumption. On the other hand, study time provides quite precise prediction, being statistically significant at the 0.001% level.

exp(coef(m1))
## (Intercept)        Medu   studytime  activities     Pstatus 
##   1.4966050   1.0612299   0.5502210   0.8362175   1.0057402
exp(confint(m1))
##                 2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 0.2544469 8.3124648
## Medu        0.8608816 1.3120240
## studytime   0.4030077 0.7375984
## activities  0.5295809 1.3198457
## Pstatus     0.4856696 2.1873461

To ease interpretation, I exponentiated the coefficients from the logistic regression, and computed their respective confidence intervals. Now, the numbers represent odds ratios. As expected, for the three variables excluding study time the estimated confidence interval contains one. This implies, that we cannot tell whether an increase in each variable increases or decreases the odds of high alcohol consumption. Considering study time, however, the confidence interval is roughly 0.40-0.74, our best guess (i.e., the odds ratio) being 0.55. The interpretation is, that increasing study time for example from 2 to 5 hours to 5 to 10 hours squeezes the odds of high alcohol consumption by about 50%. An exact interpretation is awkward, since the study time categories are not of equal size.

## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)

## Residual deviance: 448.31  on 380  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 452.31

## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4
probabilities <- predict(m2, type = "response")
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction) %>%
  prop.table() %>%
  addmargins()
##         prediction
## high_use     FALSE       Sum
##    FALSE 0.7015707 0.7015707
##    TRUE  0.2984293 0.2984293
##    Sum   1.0000000 1.0000000
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = 0)
## [1] 0.2984293
alc %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = probability, y = high_use, col = prediction)) +
  geom_point()

Finally, I evaluate the predictive power of my logistic regression. Firstly, I do this by cross-tabulating the students who actually consume high level of alcohol, and the ones my model predicts to do so. Turns out, that after excluding the statistically insignificant variables, the bivariate model with only study times as an explanatory variable predicts that none of the students is a big drinker. Thus, the confusion matrix comes out as 2x1 matrix. Regardless, it can be concluded that the proportion of inaccurately classified individuals is roughly 30%. This result is further replicated by exploiting a loss function and drawing a rather trivial plot.

In terms of predictive power, the bivariate model is worthless compared to simply guessing that none of the students is a grand alcohol consumer: both approaches produce an identical prediction error.

Based on the similarity of ranges between variables, I looked at the density of several variables simultaneously. In the dataset at hand, it seems that hardly any variable is normally distributed. While some are heavily skewed, some are bimodal, which means that they possess two distinct modes. For example, the per capita crime rate (crim) is left-skewed, while the variable proxying the proportion of blacks by town (black) is right-skewed. In addition, the variables measuring property-tax rate (tax) and the proportion of non-retail business acres (indus) appear clearly bimodal.

Considering the relationships between variables, few variables stand out when focusing on the target variable, i.e.per capita crime rate. Turns out, that quite surprisingly, property tax rate and accessibility to radial highways show the strongest positive correlation with the crime rate in a bivariate setting. Housing value, proportion of blacks and distance to employment centres experience the strongest negative correlation.

crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = T, label = c("low", "med-low", "med-high", "high"))

# Splitting the data into a train and test sets
set.seed(123)
n <- nrow(boston_scaled)
ind <- sample(n, size = n * 0.8)
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

Standardization of the data centers each variable to zero. The variables are also scaled with their respective standard deviation. In practice, this transformation moulds the variables in a way which makes their distribution closer to the standard normal distribution. After standardization, I added a new variable to the dataset, crime, which is a categorical version of the continuous variable crim. Crime was split into four equal-sized levels by first identifying its quantiles. Moreover, the old crim variable was deleted. As a last preparation before the analysis, I divided the data into train and test sets, where a random sample including 80% of the data was assigned to the train set, and the rest to the other set.

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

plot(ldam, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(ldam, myscale = 2)

Next, I fitted a linear discriminant analysis with the train set, while using the categorical crime rate as a target variable. To briefly comment the results, one distinct pattern could be pointed out. It appears, that if the train set is classified into two categories, the accessibility to radial highways is the variable which discriminates per capita crime rates the best.

Q7. K-means

# Reloading the data and computing Euclidian distances
data("Boston")

str(dist_eu)

# K-means clustering with two clusters
set.seed(123)
km <- kmeans(boston_scaled_km, centers = 2)
pairs(Boston, col = km$cluster)

# Finding the optimal number of clusters, and visualizing the results
kmax <- 10
twcss <- sapply(1:kmax, function(k){kmeans(boston_scaled_km, k)$tot.withinss})
qplot(x = 1:kmax, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

Done with the classification, I experimented a bit with clustering. Starting from a scratch, I reloaded the Boston dataset. Next, I looked a bit under the hood of k-means clustering algorithm, and created a distance matrix, which computes observations pairwise Euclidian distances. Moving on to analysis, I ran the k-means algorithm on the data with two centroids, and visualized the clusters with respect to each variable. To minimize arbitrariness when selecting the number of centroids, I computed total within cluster sum of squares to determine the optimal number of centroids, i.e.clusters. Plotting the sums with varying number of clusters from one to ten, I concluded that two clusters is indeed the optimal choice: the optimum is represented as the most distinct drop in the sum.

Based on the first glance on this weeks dataset of development indicators across 155 countries, the following patterns could be brought forward. Considering the variables distributions, it appears, that at least the ratio of participation rates between women and men and life expectancy are somewhat right-skewed, while GNI, maternal mortality ratio and adolescent birth rate appear left-skewed. The expected years of education, on the other hand, seem roughly normally distributed. According to summary statistics, secondary education, labour force participation or parliamentary representation is more common among men than women, on average. In addition, expected years of education averages around 13 years around the globe, while the mean of life expectancy is less than 72 years. Note, that these are numbers are not population-weighted.

Moving on to relations between variables, we are able to distinguish couple of strong correlations. Firstly, expected years of education and life expectancy share a distinct positive correlation, as well as maternal mortality ratio and adolescent birth rate. Furthermore, maternal mortality rate and adolescent birth rate are seemingly negatively correlated with expected years of education and life expectancy.

Once the data is standardized, the results change dramatically, since the variables become more commensurate. After the update, the first principal component captures a bit over 50% of the variability between observations, while the respective number for the second principle component is around 16%. The biplot demonstrates, that the first principle component is mainly composed of variables related to economic and social development, like gross national income, life expectancy, expected years of education, adolescent birth rate and maternal mortality ratio. One variable which does not quite fit this categorization is the ratio of women and men with secondary education. In contrast, the second principle component is driven by the parliamentary representation and the relative labor force participation of women, two features which could be wagely bundled as womens status. In conclusion, it could be stated that based on the data at hand, the variability between the countries around the globe could be approximately split into dimensions of economic development and gender inequality.

?MCA

I ran MCA with six different variables, which here refer to questions around tea-drinking habits, including preferable tea label, whether or not tea is drank during lunch etc. Turns out, that capturing the variability between the respondents in two dimensions based on the selected six questions is rather hard: the first two dimensions retain circa 30% of the overall variance, which is not that much, implying that the dimensions are not too distinguishable. Indeed, after visualizing the analysis with a biplot, it seems that we are able to classify a great mass of regular tea-drinkers, preferring Earl Grey and using mostly tea bags, from the hedonists who get their unpackaged tea from a specialized shop. However, even this categorization requires a bit of imagination.
